title: Production of no-carrier-added 139Pr via precursor decay in the proton bombardment of natPr

x4freetext: Production of no-carrier-added 139Pr via precursor
decay in the proton  bombardment of natPr

x4freetext: iThemba LABS in Faure, South Africa
All the cross-section values are for the direct
production of the particular radionuclide. In the case
of 138mPr there is no feeding from precursor decay.
In the case of the other Pr radionuclides, appropriate
corrections were made to subtract the contributions
from precursor decay.
The standard 22Na
excitation function obtained previously by means of
foil-stack activations inside a calibrated Faraday
cup, was used.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Applied Radiation and Isotopes, Vol.41, p.315 (1990)

x4freetext: The cross sections of the observed activation
products were calculated from their measured
gamma-ray emissions using disintegration data
from the catalogue of Firestone et al., Table of
Radioactive Isotopes, Version 2.1, January 2004.
Available from URL: http://ie.lbl.gov/toi.
An accurately calibrated HPGe detector with a
relative efficiency of 13%  and a resolution of
1.8 keV at 1.33 MeV was used for this purpose.
The constant component includes:
uncertainty in the beam current integration
uncertainty in the detector efficiency
uncertainty in the counting geometry
uncertainty in the decay corrections
uncertainty in the foil thickness
The total uncertainties in the measured cross
sections were obtained by summing all the contributing
uncertainties in quadrature. A variable component
includes the uncertainty due to counting statistics and
photo-peak integration as well as the uncertainty
associated with the beam-loss correction. The latter
did not exceed 1.6%.
The uncertainty in energy of each measured dat
point was estimated from the uncertainty in incident be
energy, foil thickness and depth of penetration
in the stack
Data were received from Dr. G.F.Steyn
Entry was approved by Dr. G.F.Steyn
SD
First ref. added. Statistical uncertainties
were changed on total according to final presentation
in the article.
SD: REACTION code updated according to new
EXFOR rules in Subents 012-014.
Six composite foil stacks were irradiated, two at each
primary proton-beam energy of 97.8+-0.5, 65.5+-0.4 and
39.6+-0.3 MeV. The stacks consisted of high-purity Pr
foils of 100 mu-m  thickness (99.9%), high-purity
Al monitor foils of 250 mu-m thickness (99.999%) and
groups of 125 mu-m thick Cu degrader foils (99.9%) as
required to obtain well spaced proton energies across
the entire energy region of interest.
All the foils had a diameter of 19 mm and their
individual thicknesses were determined by weighing.

tablet was thick enough to stop the beam. A primary
proton beam of 66 MeV was degraded to each desired
energy by means of an accurately machined Cu degrader
in front of each target tablet.
These irradiations were performed in an accurately
calibrated Faraday chamber
